</TABLE></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uzaknafinis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zaknafinis</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mage</span><br>  Posts: 24<br> <font color=#333333>(9/25/00 10:26:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerthingstokill.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=84.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: How to get invited into groups</span><hr size=1> This is so true.  <br>
<br>
I got into a Karnors group last night with some guildmates and some others.  Yes I know that I'm pretty low for it and yes I know that it is bad faction, but it was quite fun.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Well, the enchanter kept having to mez the mobs over and over as some of the mobs kept breaking early.  He kept asking me(the only pet class) over and over if my pet was attacking them.  Thinking that he could be right during multiple fights I made sure to /back off my pet and to reassist the main tank.  Still the mobs broke early.  My guildmates even defended me stating that you could easily see the proc from my pet hitting the mob that we were assisting.  Yet still the enchanter believed it was me I think.<br>
<br>
My point?  Just that we has magicians have two things to worry about in group.  Pet control and damage potential.  What will myself and other magicians be judged on though?  Pet control by far. <p><a href=mailto:Zaknafinis@Hotmail.com>Zaknafinis Convoquer (Shining Alliance)</a><BR>Magician of the 40th level<BR>Prexus</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uzaknafinis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zaknafinis</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10> at: 9/25/00 4:27:35 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uzantenvaliturus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zanten Valiturus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mage</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#333333>(9/25/00 10:36:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerthingstokill.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=84.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: How to get invited into groups</span><hr size=1> When in a situation like that, when you are sure your pet didn't break the mez's, there are a few causes I've found and always try to eliminate their possiblity.<br>
<br>
1) Do you have someone using dots?  Dots will make it impossible to keep a mob mezzed, because over tick the dot will do damage and break mez.<br>
<br>
2) Do you have tanks using AE procing weapons (i.e. sword of skyfire)<br>
<br>
3) Make sure everyone has a hotkey '/assist &gt;main assist&lt;' and make sure they are using it.<br>
<br>
4) Your assist changed targets at some point and not everyone changed targets with him.  Try to stress to your assist, there he should NEVER switch targets unless your enchanter (or group leader) tells you to.<br>
<br>
Hope that helps in the future.<br>
<br>
I've been blessed, I made friends with an enchanter and have almost not played since without her in my group.  The result is, she used to blame mez's on pets, now she trusts me enough that she almost always blames mez's being broke by one of the 4 above reasons. (which is 95% of the time one of those 4 reasons).  If it's my fault, I let her know (very rare) and I try my best not to let it happen again. <p><TABLE>
